    You can choose between three payment options when you purchase a Reserved Instance. With the All Upfront option, you pay for the entire Reserved Instance with one upfront payment. This option provides you with the largest discount compared to On-Demand Instance pricing. With the Partial Upfront option, you make a low upfront payment and are then charged a discounted hourly rate for the instance for the duration of the Reserved Instance term. The No Upfront option does not require any upfront payment and provides a discounted hourly rate for the duration of the term.
    All Reserved Instance types are available for Aurora, MySQL, MariaDB, PostgreSQL, Oracle and SQL Server database engines.', 'AmazonRDS', '["Reserve an Amazon RDS instance to save costs. Reserved Instances provide you with a significant discount (up to 75%) compared to On-Demand Instance pricing. You can reserve a DB instance for a one or three year term and in turn receive a significant discount compared to the On-Demand Instance pricing for the DB instance. You can choose between three payment options when you purchase a Reserved Instance. With the All Upfront option, you pay for the entire Reserved Instance with one upfront payment. This option provides you with the largest discount compared to On-Demand Instance pricing. With the Partial Upfront option, you make a low upfront payment and are then charged a discounted hourly rate for the instance for the duration of the Reserved Instance term. The No Upfront option does not require any upfront payment and provides a discounted hourly rate for the duration of the term."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://aws.amazon.com/rds/reserved-instances/"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_rds_instance_reserved', 'Configuration', 'Reserved Instance should be used for RDS Instance', 'When an AWS RDS Reserved Instance is not in use (i.e. does not have an active corresponding instance) the investment made is not exploited. For example, if you reserve a db.m3.medium RDS instance within US West (Oregon) region and you don''t provision a database instance with the same class/type, in the same region of the same AWS account or in any other linked AWS accounts within your AWS Organization, the specified RDS RI is considered unused and your investment has a negative return.', 'AmazonRDS', '["Ensure that all your AWS RDS Reserved Instances (RI) have corresponding database instances running within the same account or within any AWS accounts members of an AWS Organization (if any). A corresponding database instance is a running RDS instance that matches the reservation parameters such as Region and Instance Type."]'::jsonb, '["\n        AWS CLI and API -\n        - Use the describe-reserved-db-instances-offerings to list the Reserved DB Instance offerings available for purchase.\n        - Use the purchase-reserved-db-instances-offering command to purchase RIs for an account.\n        - Use the describe-reserved-db-instances command to list the existing RIs for an account.\n        "]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://aws.amazon.com/rds/reserved-instances/"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_rds_delete_protection', 'Configuration', 'Deletion Protection For RDS Instances', 'Deletion protection prevents any existing or new provisioned databases clusters from being terminated by a root or an IAM user, using the AWS Management Console, AWS CLI, or AWS API, unless the feature is explicitly disabled. With Deletion Protection safety feature enabled, you have the certainty that your database clusters can''t be accidentally deleted and make sure that your data remains safe.', 'AmazonRDS', '["\n        Ensure that all your provisioned Amazon Aurora database clusters are protected from accidental deletion by having the Deletion Protection feature enabled at the Aurora cluster level.\n        "]'::jsonb, '["**Terraform configuration file (.tf):**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n", "AWS CLI command to enable Deletion Protection for Aurora Cluster:\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/whats-new/2018/09/amazon-rds-now-provides-database-deletion-protection/"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_rds_storage_autoscaling', 'Configuration', 'Enable Instance Storage AutoScaling for RDS Instances', 'With the Storage AutoScaling feature enabled, when Amazon RDS detects that your database instance is running out of disk space, it automatically scales up your instance storage. For example, you can use this feature for a new mobile application that users are adopting rapidly. In this case, a rapidly increasing workload might exceed the available database storage. To avoid having to manually scale up database storage, enable Amazon RDS Storage AutoScaling.', 'AmazonRDS', '["Ensure that the Storage AutoScaling feature is enabled for your Amazon RDS database instances in order to provide dynamic scaling support for the database''s storage based on your RDS application needs. Enabling Storage AutoScaling will allow the database instance storage to increase once the configured threshold is exceeded."]'::jsonb, '["\n        **Terraform configuration file (.tf):**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n", "\n        AWS CLI command to enable Storage AutoScaling for RDS instance:\n        \\", "\\", "\\", "\n        "]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/USER_PIOPS.StorageTypes.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_rds_auto_minor_upgrade', 'Configuration', 'Auto Minor Version Upgrade For RDS', 'Amazon RDS will occasionally deprecate minor engine versions and provide new ones for upgrade. When the last version number within the release is replaced (e.g. 5.6.26 to 5.6.27), the version changed is considered minor. With the Auto Minor Version Upgrade feature enabled, the version upgrades will occur automatically during the specified maintenance window and your database instances will get the new features, the bug fixes, and the security patches for their database engines.', 'AmazonRDS', '["\n        Ensure that your Amazon RDS database instances have the Auto Minor Version Upgrade flag enabled in order to receive automatically minor engine upgrades during the specified maintenance window. Each version upgrade is available only after is tested and approved by AWS.\n        "]'::jsonb, '["\n        **Terraform configuration file (.tf):**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n", "\n        AWS CLI command to enable Auto Minor Version Upgrade for RDS instance:\n        \\", "\\", "\\", "\n        "]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/USER_UpgradeDBInstance.Upgrading.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_rds_performance_insights', 'Configuration', 'Performance Insights Should Be Enabled for RDS Instances', 'The Performance Insights feature provides you instant visibility into the nature of the workloads on your Amazon RDS databases and helps you find the cause of any performance issue found on your databases.', 'AmazonRDS', '["\n        Ensure that your Amazon RDS MySQL and PostgreSQL database instances have the Performance Insights feature enabled in order to allow you to obtain a better overview of your databases performance as well as help you to identify potential performance issues. Performance Insights is a performance monitoring tool that helps you to evaluate the load on your MySQL/PostgreSQL databases and determine when and where to take action. The feature allows you to detect performance bottlenecks with an easy-to-understand dashboard that visualizes database load in real time. For example, with Performance Insights feature enabled, when the load of your database is high, you can easily determine the type of bottleneck such as high CPU consumption, lock waits or I/O latency, and see which SQL queries are creating the bottleneck. Performance Insights is currently available for the following database engines: Amazon Aurora (MySQL and PostgreSQL-compatible editions), RDS MySQL, and RDS PostgreSQL.\n        "]'::jsonb, '["\n        **Terraform configuration file (.tf):**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n", "AWS CLI command to enable Performance Insights for RDS instance:\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n        "]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/USER_PerfInsights.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_rds_backup_enabled', 'Configuration', 'Automated Backups Enabled for RDS Instances', 'Creating point-in-time database instance snapshots periodically will allow you to handle efficiently your data restoration process in the event of a user error on the source database or to save data before making a major change to the instance database such as changing the structure of a table.', 'AmazonRDS', '["Ensure that your Amazon RDS database instances have automated backups enabled for point-in-time recovery. To back up your database instances, Amazon RDS takes automatically a full daily snapshot of your data (with transactions logs) during the specified backup window and keeps the backups for a specified period of time (known as retention period)."]'::jsonb, '["\n        **Terraform configuration file (.tf):**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n", "AWS CLI command to enable Automated Backups for RDS instance:\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://aws.amazon.com/rds/features/backup/"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_rds_backupservice_enabled', 'Configuration', 'AWS Backup Service in Use for Amazon RDS', 'With Amazon Backup, you can centrally configure backup policies and rules, and monitor backup activity for AWS RDS database instances. The Backup service automates and consolidates backup tasks previously performed service-by-service, removing the need to create custom scripts such as Lambda functions and manual processes.', 'AmazonRDS', '["\n        Ensure that Amazon Backup is integrated with Amazon Relational Database Service (RDS) in order to manage RDS database instance snapshots and improve the reliability of your backup strategy. Amazon Backup is a fully managed service that creates, restores and deletes backups on your behalf.\n        "]'::jsonb, '["\n        Create Backup Plan for RDS Database Instance:\n        \\", "\\", "\\", "\n        "]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://aws.amazon.com/rds/features/backup/"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_rds_copy_tags_to_snapshots', 'Configuration', 'Enable Copy Tags to Snapshots for RDS Instances', 'Copying your Amazon Aurora database cluster tags to any automated or manual snapshots taken from your database clusters allows you to easily set metadata (including access policies) on your snapshots in order to match the parent clusters.', 'AmazonRDS', '["Ensure that your Amazon Aurora database clusters make use of Copy Tags to Snapshots feature in order to allow tags set on your Aurora database clusters to be automatically copied to any automated or manual snapshots that are created from these clusters. Once the feature is enabled, tags can be copied to all future copies of an Amazon Aurora snapshots, including cross-region snapshots."]'::jsonb, '["\n        **Terraform configuration file (.tf):**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n", "\n        AWS CLI command to enable Copy Tags to Snapshots for RDS Cluster:\n        \\", "\\", "\\", "\n        "]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/USER_Tagging.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_s3_versioning', 'Configuration', 'Bucket Versioning should be enabled for S3 Buckets', 'Versioning-enabled Amazon S3 buckets will allow you to preserve, retrieve, and restore every version of an S3 object. S3 versioning can be used for data protection and retention scenarios such as recovering objects that have been accidentally/intentionally deleted or overwritten by AWS users or applications and archiving previous versions of objects to Amazon S3 Glacier for long-term low-cost storage. With S3 versioning, you can easily recover from both unintended user actions and application failures.', 'AmazonS3', '["Ensure that S3 object versioning is enabled for your Amazon S3 buckets in order to preserve and recover overwritten and deleted S3 objects as an extra layer of data protection and/or data retention."]'::jsonb, '["\n        **Terraform configuration file (.tf):**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n", "\n        AWS CLI command to enable Versioning for S3 bucket:\n        \\", "\\", "\\", "\n        "]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/Versioning.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_s3_lifecycle', 'Configuration', 'Lifecycle Configuration Enabled for S3 Buckets', 'With an S3 lifecycle configuration, you can enable Amazon S3 to downgrade the storage class for your objects, archive or delete S3 objects during their lifecycle. For example, you can define S3 lifecycle configuration rules to achieve compliance (with the law, with your organization standards or business requirements) by automatically transitioning your objects to S3 Standard-Infrequent Access (S3 Standard-IA) storage class one month after creation, or archive S3 objects with Amazon S3 Glacier using Glacier or Glacier Deep Archive storage class one year after creation. You can also implement lifecycle configuration rules to expire (delete) objects based on your retention requirements or clean up incomplete multipart uploads in order to optimize your Amazon S3 costs.', 'AmazonS3', '["Ensure that your Amazon S3 buckets are using lifecycle configurations for security and cost optimization purposes. An S3 lifecycle configuration is a set of one or more rules, where each rule defines an action (transition or expiration action) for Amazon S3 to apply to a group of objects. A lifecycle configuration is used to manage Amazon S3 data during its lifetime."]'::jsonb, '["**Terraform configuration file (.tf):**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n", " AWS CLI command to enable Lifecycle Configuration for S3 bucket:\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/object-lifecycle-mgmt.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_elasticache_auto_minor_upgrade', 'Configuration', 'Minor Version Upgrade Enabled for ElastiCache Clusters', 'Amazon ElasticCache will occasionally deprecate minor engine versions and provide new ones for upgrade. When the last version number within the release is replaced (e.g. 5.6.26 to 5.6.27), the version changed is considered minor. With the Auto Minor Version Upgrade feature enabled, the version upgrades will occur automatically during the specified maintenance window and your database instances will get the new features, the bug fixes, and the security patches for their database engines.', 'AmazonElastiCache', '["\n        Ensure that your Amazon ElasticCache cluster instances have the Auto Minor Version Upgrade flag enabled in order to receive automatically minor engine upgrades during the specified maintenance window. Each version upgrade is available only after is tested and approved by AWS.\n        "]'::jsonb, '["**Terraform configuration file (.tf):**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n        ", "\n        AWS CLI command to enable Auto Minor Version Upgrade for ElastiCache cluster:\n        \\", "\\", "\\", "\n        "]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonElastiCache/latest/red-ug/VersionManagement.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_service_min_healthy_percent_low', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Service Minimum Healthy Percent Too Low', 'The Fargate service minimum healthy percent is below 50%, which may impact availability during deployments.', 'AWSFargate', '["Set minimum healthy percent to at least 50% for services with multiple tasks to maintain availability during rolling deployments."]'::jsonb, '["minimumHealthyPercent"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/service_definition_parameters.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_service_min_healthy_percent_too_low_for_single_task', 'Configuration', 'Single-Task Fargate Service Minimum Healthy Percent Below 100%', 'For a single-task service, minimum healthy percent less than 100% can cause downtime during updates.', 'AWSFargate', '["Set minimum healthy percent to 100% for single-task services to avoid downtime during deployments."]'::jsonb, '["minimumHealthyPercent"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/service_definition_parameters.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_service_max_percent_non_standard', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Service Maximum Percent Non-Standard', 'The maximum percent deployment configuration is not set to the standard 200%.', 'AWSFargate', '["Review if the non-standard maximum percent is intentional. Standard is 200% to allow rolling deployments."]'::jsonb, '["maximumPercent"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/service_definition_parameters.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_service_health_check_grace_period_zero', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Service Health Check Grace Period Is Zero', 'The health check grace period is set to 0, which may cause tasks to be terminated before they finish starting up.', 'AWSFargate', '["Set a health check grace period that gives tasks enough time to start up and pass health checks."]'::jsonb, '["healthCheckGracePeriodSeconds"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/service_definition_parameters.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_service_exec_enabled', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Service ECS Exec Is Enabled', 'ECS Exec is enabled on this Fargate service. This feature allows interactive shell access to running containers and should be disabled in production.', 'AWSFargate', '["Disable ECS Exec on production services to reduce the attack surface. Only enable it for debugging when needed."]'::jsonb, '["enableExecuteCommand"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/ecs-exec.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_task_definition_cpu_undefined', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Task Definition CPU Not Defined', 'The Fargate task definition does not have CPU units defined, which can lead to unpredictable resource allocation.', 'AWSFargate', '["Define CPU units in the task definition to ensure predictable resource allocation."]'::jsonb, '["cpu"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task_definition_parameters.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_task_definition_memory_undefined', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Task Definition Memory Not Defined', 'The Fargate task definition does not have memory defined, which can lead to unpredictable resource allocation.', 'AWSFargate', '["Define memory in the task definition to ensure predictable resource allocation."]'::jsonb, '["memory"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task_definition_parameters.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_task_definition_missing_task_role', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Task Definition Missing Task Role', 'The task definition does not have an IAM task role assigned. Without a task role, containers cannot securely access AWS services.', 'AWSFargate', '["Assign an IAM task role to the task definition following the principle of least privilege."]'::jsonb, '["taskRoleArn"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task-iam-roles.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_task_definition_image_latest_tag', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Task Definition Using Latest Image Tag', 'The container image uses the :latest tag, which makes deployments non-deterministic and harder to rollback.', 'AWSFargate', '["Use specific image tags or digests instead of :latest to ensure reproducible deployments."]'::jsonb, '["Update the container definition to use a specific image tag (e.g., v1.2.3 or a SHA digest)."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task_definition_parameters.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_task_definition_logging_not_configured', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Task Definition Logging Not Configured', 'The container does not have logging configured, which makes it difficult to troubleshoot issues.', 'AWSFargate', '["Configure a log driver (e.g., awslogs) for all containers in the task definition."]'::jsonb, '["logConfiguration"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/using_awslogs.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_fargate_task_definition_health_check_not_configured', 'Configuration', 'Fargate Task Definition Health Check Not Configured', 'The container does not have a health check configured, which means unhealthy containers may not be detected.', 'AWSFargate', '["Configure a health check for containers to enable automatic detection and replacement of unhealthy tasks."]'::jsonb, '["healthCheck"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task_definition_parameters.html#container_definition_healthcheck"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_redshift_audit_logging', 'Configuration', 'Redshift Audit Logging Should Be Enabled', 'Amazon Redshift audit logging provides information about connections and user activities in your cluster.', 'AmazonRedshift', '["Enable audit logging for your Redshift cluster to track database activity for security and compliance purposes."]'::jsonb, '["aws redshift modify-cluster --cluster-identifier {{recommendation.cluster_id}} --logging-properties BucketName=my-bucket"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/mgmt/db-auditing.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_redshift_snapshot_retention', 'Configuration', 'Redshift Snapshot Retention Period Should Be Configured', 'The Redshift cluster snapshot retention period should be set to ensure backups are maintained for an adequate period.', 'AmazonRedshift', '["Configure an appropriate snapshot retention period for your Redshift cluster."]'::jsonb, '["aws redshift modify-cluster --cluster-identifier {{recommendation.cluster_id}} --automated-snapshot-retention-period 7"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/mgmt/working-with-snapshots.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_guardduty_enabled', 'Configuration', 'GuardDuty Should Be Enabled', 'Amazon GuardDuty is a threat detection service that continuously monitors for malicious activity and unauthorized behavior.', 'AmazonGuardDuty', '["Enable GuardDuty in all regions to detect threats across your AWS environment."]'::jsonb, '["\n**Enable GuardDuty:**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_settingup.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_guardduty_detector_active', 'Configuration', 'GuardDuty Detector Should Be Active', 'The GuardDuty detector exists but is not in an active state, meaning threats are not being monitored.', 'AmazonGuardDuty', '["Ensure the GuardDuty detector is active to continuously monitor for threats."]'::jsonb, '["\n**Activate the detector:**\n\\", "\\", "\\", "\n"]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_settingup.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_guardduty_s3_logs_enabled', 'Configuration', 'GuardDuty S3 Protection Should Be Enabled', 'GuardDuty S3 Protection monitors S3 data access events to detect suspicious activity.', 'AmazonGuardDuty', '["Enable S3 Protection in GuardDuty to monitor S3 bucket access for threats."]'::jsonb, '["Update the detector to enable S3 logs data source."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/s3-protection.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_guardduty_k8s_audit_logs_enabled', 'Configuration', 'GuardDuty Kubernetes Audit Logs Should Be Enabled', 'GuardDuty EKS Protection monitors Kubernetes audit logs for suspicious activity in EKS clusters.', 'AmazonGuardDuty', '["Enable Kubernetes audit log monitoring in GuardDuty for EKS cluster threat detection."]'::jsonb, '["Update the detector to enable Kubernetes data source."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/kubernetes-protection.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_es_dedicated_master', 'Configuration', 'Elasticsearch Dedicated Master Nodes Should Be Enabled', 'Dedicated master nodes improve cluster stability by offloading cluster management tasks from data nodes.', 'AmazonES', '["Enable dedicated master nodes for production Elasticsearch domains to improve stability."]'::jsonb, '["Update the domain configuration to enable dedicated master nodes with at least 3 instances."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/opensearch-service/latest/developerguide/managedomains-dedicatedmasternodes.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_es_audit_logs_enabled', 'Configuration', 'Elasticsearch Audit Logs Should Be Enabled', 'Audit logs capture user activity in your Elasticsearch domain for security monitoring and compliance.', 'AmazonES', '["Enable audit logs for your Elasticsearch domain to track user activity."]'::jsonb, '["Update the domain log publishing options to enable audit logs."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/opensearch-service/latest/developerguide/audit-logs.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_es_slow_logs_enabled', 'Configuration', 'Elasticsearch Slow Logs Should Be Enabled', 'Slow logs help identify performance bottlenecks in your Elasticsearch domain.', 'AmazonES', '["Enable slow logs to identify and troubleshoot query and indexing performance issues."]'::jsonb, '["Update the domain log publishing options to enable slow logs."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/opensearch-service/latest/developerguide/createdomain-configure-slow-logs.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_directconnect_connection_down', 'Configuration', 'Direct Connect Connection Is Down', 'The Direct Connect connection is not in an available state, which may impact network connectivity.', 'AWSDirectConnect', '["Investigate and resolve the Direct Connect connection issue to restore connectivity."]'::jsonb, '["Check the AWS Direct Connect console for connection status and contact AWS Support if needed."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/WorkingWithConnections.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_directconnect_no_redundancy', 'Configuration', 'Direct Connect Has No Redundancy', 'The Direct Connect setup does not have redundant connections, creating a single point of failure.', 'AWSDirectConnect', '["Set up redundant Direct Connect connections for high availability."]'::jsonb, '["Create a second Direct Connect connection at a different location for redundancy."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/getting_started.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_directconnect_no_virtual_interfaces', 'Configuration', 'Direct Connect Has No Virtual Interfaces', 'The Direct Connect connection has no virtual interfaces configured.', 'AWSDirectConnect', '["Configure virtual interfaces on the Direct Connect connection to establish connectivity."]'::jsonb, '["Create a virtual interface on the Direct Connect connection."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/WorkingWithVirtualInterfaces.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_directconnect_lag_below_minimum', 'Configuration', 'Direct Connect LAG Below Minimum Connections', 'The Link Aggregation Group has fewer active connections than the minimum threshold.', 'AWSDirectConnect', '["Ensure the LAG has sufficient active connections for required bandwidth."]'::jsonb, '["Add more connections to the LAG or reduce the minimum links threshold."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/lags.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_directconnect_lag_down', 'Configuration', 'Direct Connect LAG Is Down', 'The Direct Connect Link Aggregation Group is not operational.', 'AWSDirectConnect', '["Investigate and resolve the LAG issue to restore connectivity."]'::jsonb, '["Check the LAG status and ensure member connections are active."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/lags.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_directconnect_vif_down', 'Configuration', 'Direct Connect Virtual Interface Is Down', 'The Direct Connect virtual interface is not in an available state.', 'AWSDirectConnect', '["Investigate and resolve the virtual interface issue."]'::jsonb, '["Check the VIF status and ensure BGP session is established."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/WorkingWithVirtualInterfaces.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_directconnect_bgp_peer_down', 'Configuration', 'Direct Connect BGP Peer Is Down', 'The BGP peer on the Direct Connect virtual interface is not established.', 'AWSDirectConnect', '["Investigate the BGP peer issue and restore the session."]'::jsonb, '["Verify BGP configuration on both sides and check for network issues."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/WorkingWithVirtualInterfaces.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_elb_cross_zone_balancing', 'Configuration', 'ELB Cross-Zone Load Balancing Should Be Enabled', 'Cross-zone load balancing distributes traffic evenly across all registered instances in all enabled Availability Zones.', 'AmazonELB', '["Enable cross-zone load balancing to ensure even traffic distribution across AZs."]'::jsonb, '["aws elb modify-load-balancer-attributes --load-balancer-name {{resource_name}} --load-balancer-attributes \"{\"CrossZoneLoadBalancing\":{\"Enabled\":true}}\""]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/classic/enable-disable-crosszone-lb.html"]'::jsonb),
  ('aws_elb_connection_draining', 'Configuration', 'ELB Connection Draining Should Be Enabled', 'Connection draining ensures that the load balancer completes in-flight requests before deregistering instances.', 'AmazonELB', '["Enable connection draining to allow in-flight requests to complete during instance deregistration."]'::jsonb, '["Enable connection draining with an appropriate timeout value."]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '["https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/classic/config-conn-drain.html"]'::jsonb)
